1
00:00:04,866 --> 00:00:09,013
When I've read this statement of Prabhupad in his "Bhagavad-gita as it is",

2
00:00:09,013 --> 00:00:09,886
and he said...

3
00:00:09,886 --> 00:00:12,180
[I Need Divine Intervention!]

4
00:00:12,180 --> 00:00:16,072
He says it so matter-of-factly,
but it's very profound.

5
00:00:16,072 --> 00:00:23,492
It's in the "tad viddhi praṇipātena, paripraśnena sevayā" section,

6
00:00:23,492 --> 00:00:27,492
upadekṣyanti te jñānaṁ, jñāninas tattva-darśinaḥ — 
about accepting a guru.

7
00:00:27,777 --> 00:00:35,927
And he said, "For one who realizes that 
material existence is a constant
source of perplexity,

8
00:00:35,943 --> 00:00:41,073
it behooves such a person to take shelter
of a spiritual master".

9
00:00:41,073 --> 00:00:44,667
So I've some times paraphrased this
to my friends by saying,

10
00:00:44,667 --> 00:00:51,555
"Yes, life sometimes is a never-ending
series of humiliations".

11
00:00:51,555 --> 00:00:53,412
You say, "What is life?"

12
00:00:53,412 --> 00:00:58,112
Dostoevsky says in one of his 
"Notes From the Underground",

13
00:00:58,137 --> 00:01:06,687
he says that, 
"Humiliation is one of the most intense forms
of self-awareness and consciousness".

14
00:01:07,870 --> 00:01:13,560
Not just being humble — being humiliated.
There is a little difference there.

15
00:01:13,784 --> 00:01:17,636
"Humble" has this dignified ring to it;

16
00:01:17,636 --> 00:01:23,498
"humiliated" is not something we strive for.

17
00:01:26,118 --> 00:01:32,720
Which reminds me of one British essayist, who was giving advice to writers.

18
00:01:32,720 --> 00:01:36,240
He said, "Make sure you spellcheck everything you write",

19
00:01:36,240 --> 00:01:42,080
he said, "Because if words are misspelled, people will think that you are stupid".

20
00:01:42,080 --> 00:01:45,985
And he said, "Rarely will you want to give them that impression".

21
00:01:46,565 --> 00:01:49,200
[laughs]

22
00:01:49,200 --> 00:01:53,637
So anyway, humiliation is one of the most intense forms of consciousness,

23
00:01:53,637 --> 00:01:58,457
and what is... to continue with Dostoevsky, what does he say? He said,

24
00:01:58,457 --> 00:02:04,441
"I was amazed by my capacity", he said, "In one moment

25
00:02:04,441 --> 00:02:12,362
to be rasing my glass in a toast to the highest, the best, the most divine",

26
00:02:12,800 --> 00:02:16,308
he said, "And in the next moment capable of sinking

27
00:02:16,308 --> 00:02:20,636
into the most horrible slime of sinful activities.

28
00:02:20,636 --> 00:02:23,474
That I've observed about myself.

29
00:02:23,474 --> 00:02:26,552
And that was quite humiliating".

30
00:02:26,552 --> 00:02:31,360
"So one minute I've got a tear coming down my cheek praising what is high,

31
00:02:31,360 --> 00:02:36,820
and in the next moment I'm in the swamp of ignorance,

32
00:02:36,820 --> 00:02:40,626
the worst type of ignorance and misconception".

33
00:02:40,626 --> 00:02:47,092
So, a sincere aspirant, just like in the song we sing everyday:

34
00:02:47,092 --> 00:02:52,982
jogyatā-vichāre, kichu nāhi pāi,
tomāra koruṇā-sāra,

35
00:02:53,205 --> 00:02:57,213
the disciple is praying to guru sayng,

36
00:02:57,413 --> 00:03:02,221
"If you examine me really,
you'll find nothing salvageable,

37
00:03:02,221 --> 00:03:06,729
nothing worth saving, there's nothing here [indistinct]".

38
00:03:06,729 --> 00:03:11,589
It's not, "I have, I'm so valuable, and with a little bit of adjustment..."

39
00:03:11,589 --> 00:03:13,909
No. He's sayng, "No value.

40
00:03:13,909 --> 00:03:17,866
But through your connection,
by your grace, your mercy —

41
00:03:17,909 --> 00:03:21,509
Sri Guru and His Grace —
by the grace of Sri Guru

42
00:03:21,509 --> 00:03:26,139
you can take me from the imperfection plane
to the perfectional stage.

43
00:03:26,139 --> 00:03:30,246
That I believe. That miracle is possible
by your connection".

44
00:03:31,533 --> 00:03:34,625
And Guru Maharaj will say,

45
00:03:34,625 --> 00:03:39,377
"To come out of the mud, you may have to walk through the mud for some time".

46
00:03:39,377 --> 00:03:42,319
To come out of the mud of misconception

47
00:03:42,319 --> 00:03:46,561
we may have to walk through
the mud of misconception for some time.

48
00:03:46,561 --> 00:03:48,826
But we will need a proper direction.

49
00:03:48,826 --> 00:03:52,031
But that is like call-and-response.

50
00:03:52,031 --> 00:03:56,386
We are expressing our sincerity and our need,

51
00:03:56,386 --> 00:04:02,616
"I need shelter. I want shelter. I acknowledge my limitations.

52
00:04:02,616 --> 00:04:07,825
What is there?
dainya, ātma-nivedana, goptṛtve varaṇa,

53
00:04:07,825 --> 00:04:09,427
even though Guru Maharaj is saying,

54
00:04:09,427 --> 00:04:14,859
"Jiva Gosvami identifying goptṛtve varaṇa
as the primary anga".

55
00:04:14,859 --> 00:04:18,573
But what is... interestingly, what has Bhaktivinod began in his song —

56
00:04:18,573 --> 00:04:23,234
"dainya", which can really
be rendered various ways,

57
00:04:23,234 --> 00:04:26,605
but one way is to say

58
00:04:26,605 --> 00:04:30,168
"hopeless", "desperate".

59
00:04:30,168 --> 00:04:35,473
"Desperately hopeless". 
Or "hopelessly desperate".

60
00:04:35,473 --> 00:04:38,982
Where someone makes a real careful
assessment of, like,

61
00:04:38,982 --> 00:04:42,571
"What is the world, who it is I think I am",

62
00:04:42,571 --> 00:04:46,150
acknowledges the misconception that they're under

63
00:04:46,150 --> 00:04:49,793
and prays for some divine intervention.

64
00:04:49,793 --> 00:04:51,166
Some help.

65
00:04:52,916 --> 00:04:54,070
Hare Krishna.

